The Waiter Robot employs a distributed, multi-microcontroller architecture to execute autonomous navigation, environmental perception, and vision-based table recognition. The low-level motion-control layer is managed by an Arduino Nano, which interfaces with a 5-channel IR reflectance array for black-line tracking, an HC-SR04 ultrasonic sensor for obstacle detection, and an MPU6050 inertial measurement unit (IMU) to acquire triaxial accelerometer data (X, Y, Z) and orientation angles (roll, pitch, yaw). Actuation is handled by a TB6612FNG motor driver, which receives PWM speed signals and direction logic from the Nano to govern the drivetrain.

The intermediate processing layer is built around an ESP32, which communicates with the Arduino Nano via a full-duplex UART serial link (Serial0). The ESP32 integrates a TCS3200 color sensor for chromatic recognition, an analog current sensor and a resistive voltage divider (both connected to dedicated ADC channels) for real-time power monitoring, and two optical encoders whose quadrature pulses are processed to calculate individual wheel speeds in meters per second using standard odometry formulae. A peripheral OLED display (I²C interface) serves as the human–machine interface (HMI), rendering live metrics including bus voltage, current draw, motor velocities, and detected color values.

High-level vision processing is delegated to an ESP32-CAM coprocessor, tethered to the ESP32 via a secondary UART channel (Serial2). The ESP32-CAM executes an on-device TinyML classification model, trained via Edge Impulse to recognize numerical table identifiers (1 through 4). Upon a successful inference, the coprocessor logs the captured image to its onboard MicroSD card and transmits a "RIGHT" command string to the ESP32 over the serial link. The ESP32 subsequently relays this command to the Arduino Nano, which immediately interrupts all active control routines—including line-following and obstacle-avoidance loops—and executes a predefined right-turn maneuver to approach the detected table.
